HEADWORD: Whinyard
<hw>Whin"yard</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Prov. E. &
Scot. <ets>whingar</ets>, <ets>whinger</ets>; perhaps from AS.
<ets>winn</ets> contention, war + <ets>geard</ets>, <ets>gyrd</ets>, a
staff, rod, yard; or cf. AS. <ets>hw⟦imac⟧nan</ets> to whistle, E.
<ets>whine</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sword, or hanger.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[From the shape of the bill.]</ety>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The shoveler.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The poachard.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

